\end{equation}
The standard enthalpy of formation of an element in its most stable standard state is zero. For iodine, the stable standard state is solid \(\ce{I_{2}(s)}\). Therefore:
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)}) = 0\ \text{kJ¡¤mol}^{-1}
\end{equation}
Now, we can calculate \(\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus}\):
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus} = 62.4\ \text{kJ¡¤mol}^{-1} - 0\ \text{kJ¡¤mol}^{-1} = 62.4\ \text{kJ¡¤mol}^{-1}
\end{equation}
For consistency in units with entropy, we convert this to Joules per mole:
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{sub}H_{m}^{\ominus} = 62.4 \times 1000\ \text{J¡¤mol}^{-1} = 62400\ \text{J¡¤mol}^{-1}
